65d9ec45-1ce4-5c73-979b-605437062ac9,tg:rubgr:7,e73_Descriptions,,id.desc,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,"[recto] Catal.N°2: Landscape with Christ Calling Peter; [kantlijn links] The smaller rock in the water in Christ Landscape very similar to Rocks in de Boer; Very near to De Boer Landscape: Trees at edges of rocks silhouetted in the same way. The composition: river leading straight into depth (not diagonal) the same, with flanking rocks in foreground, higher as left, lower on right. The structure (and texture) of the rocks different. Sharp brittle in Christ Landscape softer in de Boer picture. Lighting the rains: dark foreground light in background. Rocks seen silhouetted against the light. Boats with figures in water in both;The Figures in Christ calling Peter. The 2 men at the shore, cf. men in Insidiosus Auceps (B. 10). Sheep cf. Plaustrum Belgicum (B. II) Christ cf. Joseph & Virgin in Fuga Deiparae Aegyptum (B.15); for drapery of Christ also Magdalene Poenitens (B.8). The straight orthogonal foreshortening – instead of the later diagonal - of the river also in Prospectus Tyburtinus (B.3); [verso] The birch tree trunk lying on the road precursor of tree trunk in Children’s Games and the trunk on right in ‘February’. Waves not quite to wild, but related in character to waves in ‘Shipwreck’ by Bles in Napels (Baldass Jb.34, 1918, Fig.26) [= Ludwig Baldass, Die niederländische Landschaftsmalerei von Patinir bis Bruegel, in: Jahrbuch der kunsthistorischen Sammlungen in Wien, 34 (1918), Heft 4, pp. 112-157]; The tiny figures in the field – very fine like in de Boer & in later pictures e.g. Stuyck Landscape.[scan]",descriptive note,Nederlands,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,

column4: <content>[recto] Catal.N°2: Landscape with Christ Calling Peter; [kantlijn links] The smaller rock in the water in Christ Landscape very similar to Rocks in de Boer; Very near to De Boer Landscape: Trees at edges of rocks silhouetted in the same way. The composition: river leading straight into depth (not diagonal) the same, with flanking rocks in foreground, higher as left, lower on right. The structure (and texture) of the rocks different. Sharp brittle in Christ Landscape softer in de Boer picture. Lighting the rains: dark foreground light in background. Rocks seen silhouetted against the light. Boats with figures in water in both;The Figures in Christ calling Peter. The 2 men at the shore, cf. men in Insidiosus Auceps (B. 10). Sheep cf. Plaustrum Belgicum (B. II) Christ cf. Joseph & Virgin in Fuga Deiparae Aegyptum (B.15); for drapery of Christ also Magdalene Poenitens (B.8). The straight orthogonal foreshortening – instead of the later diagonal - of the river also in Prospectus Tyburtinus (B.3); [verso] The birch tree trunk lying on the road precursor of tree trunk in Children’s Games and the trunk on right in ‘February’. Waves not quite to wild, but related in character to waves in ‘Shipwreck’ by Bles in Napels (Baldass Jb.34, 1918, Fig.26) [= Ludwig Baldass, Die niederländische Landschaftsmalerei von Patinir bis Bruegel, in: Jahrbuch der kunsthistorischen Sammlungen in Wien, 34 (1918), Heft 4, pp. 112-157]; The tiny figures in the field – very fine like in de Boer & in later pictures e.g. Stuyck Landscape.[scan]</content>
<object.title>Landscape with Christ appearing to the apostles at the sea of Tiberias</object.title>
